caption: I had an awesome time at this spot. We liked the great atmosphere and the food. The staff were very attentive. I am happy we finally managed to visit this restaurant.

I've had great food and entertainment each time I've been in SMOKE Jazz and Supper Club, both late night jam sessions with super cocktails, and a dinner set with a perfectly cooked New York steak and top notch wines. The staff is outstanding and friendly, cater to your needs and make you feel at home and like one of the family. I come all the way from the west coast and would rather make the trip there go to any club in LA, Seattle, or Phoenix, where I've lived before. The upper west side is laid back and relaxed, the music and the club fit the Strauss Park area like a glove, and the prices are very reasonable for New York City. Can't wait till the pandemic is over to head back to NYC and have another round at SMOKE, a great place, gold star in every regard!

Our dinner at Smoke Jazz & Supper Club was an AMAZING experience.  The food was perfectly prepared and presented.  So much attention to detail!!!! Servers do not enter the pods, and practiced very strict safety protocols. This was our family's first outdoor dining experience in a very loooong time- and we would 10000% return for another meal at Smoke Jazz. Smoke Jazz & Supper Club presents world-class jazz seven nights a week. Candlelit tables, plush velvet banquets, antique chandeliers, and an historic full-length bar create a real jazz vibe. Smoke also serves the perfect complement to classic jazz— soulful American cuisine. The room has seating for just over fifty, which ensures that every listener is close to the action. During Smoke's renovation, the primary focus was on creating an unparalleled room for music...and it shows. The acoustics are some of the best anywhere. Pianist David Hazeltine remarked, “I love playing this room. It’s rare that the piano can be heard as clearly as it is in this club.” Harold Mabern added, “It’s the best jazz club in the world.” In the almost 20 years since its opening, jazz has continued to thrive at 106th (aka Duke Ellington Boulevard) and Broadway and Smoke is adding a few new chapters of history to a location that has been host to a legendary jazz venue for over 40 years. Smoke was named “Best New Jazz Club” in 2000 by New York Magazine and has won the open table diner's choice awards for several consecutive years.

The show and the meal cost about $380 for three people after tax and tip.  As far as the food goes, I got calamari and the buttermilk fried chicken. The calamari was good, but the chicken was not discernibly different from Popeyes. My fiancée got the short ribs which were overcooked and tough. My father got the seared salmon which was good. Dessert consisted of two macarons about the width of a dime.  With regards to the show, we saw Steve Turre who is a world renowned trombonist in these styles. However, the song selection and solos were “adequate” but not more impressive than anything I’ve heard at a university recital or a small jazz club.  The show was about one hour long, and after we felt rushed to leave as they had to “flip” the room for the next show. We left feeling like we had spent a lot of money but not sure why - the food, music, and atmosphere didn’t really justify, and we could have easily found a similar or better experience for much less money.  In reflecting on the experience, I can’t say that I would ever go back here, or recommend anyone to visit. Smoke is making a tremendous amount of money on this schtick, perhaps partially riding on their reputation. But unlike some of the other established venues in the city, this one didn’t really provide an experience worthy of the hype.

Good music & decent food. Dessert was great (we had the creen brûlée). However, main entrees are over priced for the portion and quality. There is also a music surcharge, which seems a bit much. Staff was a bit rude. The space was small and there where two lines of tables packed for an elbow to elbow setting. Stage was small, but the band that played was great.
Prix fix is not worth the cost, good was mediocre at best. They charge extra $9/ person for the music. Not sure I'll come back here.
